The intersection of sets A and B, denoted as A ∩ B, is the set of elements that are common to both A and B.

A = {2, 4, 6, 8}
B = {4, 8, 12}

A ∩ B = {4, 8}

Now, we need to prove that the intersection A ∩ B is a subset of both A and B.

A subset is a set whose elements are all members of another set. In this case, we need to show that all elements of A ∩ B are members of both A and B.

Let's check each element of A ∩ B:

1. 4 is an element of A ∩ B. It is also an element of A and an element of B.
2. 8 is an element of A ∩ B. It is also an element of A and an element of B.

Since all elements of A ∩ B are elements of both A and B, we can conclude that A ∩ B is a subset of both A and B.
